Newton-Raphson Solver: Create a flopy nwt package object¶

In [7]:
# Newton-Raphson Solver: Create a flopy nwt package object

headtol = 1.0e-4
fluxtol = 5
maxiterout = 5000
thickfact = 1e-06
linmeth = 2
iprnwt = 1
ibotav = 1

nwt = flopy.modflow.ModflowNwt(
    mf,
    headtol=headtol,
    fluxtol=fluxtol,
    maxiterout=maxiterout,
    thickfact=thickfact,
    linmeth=linmeth,
    iprnwt=iprnwt,
    ibotav=ibotav,
    options="SIMPLE",
)

# Stress periods [5year, 5year...]; time steps within 1 stress period [1year, 1year, ...]
Steady = np.zeros(40, dtype=bool)
nstp = np.ones(40, dtype = int)*5
tsmult = np.ones(40)*1.0

perlen = np.ones(40)*365*5

nper = len(perlen)
print(nper)

#layercbd: An array of flags indicating whether or not a layer has a Quasi-3D confining bed below it.
laycbd = 0 

# Create the discretization object
# itmuni = 4 (days); lenuni = 2 (meter)
dis = flopy.modflow.ModflowDis(
    mf,
    nlay,
    nrow,
    ncol,
    nper=nper,
    delr=delr,
    delc=delc,
    top=topElev,
    botm=botm,
    laycbd=laycbd,
    itmuni=4,
    lenuni=2,
    steady=Steady,
    nstp=nstp,
    tsmult=tsmult,
    perlen=perlen,
)

Instantiate the UPW right after DIS for write_input()¶

In [15]:
# UPW must be instantiated after DIS.  Otherwise, during the mf.write_input() procedures,
# flopy will crash.

# First line of UPW input is: IUPWCB HDRY NPUPW IPHDRY
hdry = -1.00e30
iphdry = 0

# Next variables are: LAYTYP, LAYAVG, CHANI, LAYVKA, LAYWET
laytyp = [1, 3, 3]  # >0: convertible
layavg = 0  #  0: harmonic mean
chani = 1.0  # >0: CHANI is the horizontal anisotropy for the entire layer
layvka = 0  # =0: indicates VKA is vertical hydraulic conductivity
laywet = 0  # Always set equal to zero in UPW package
# hani = 1  # Not needed because CHANI > 1
In [16]:
hk1 = np.ones(topElev.shape)*11.3

#pd.DataFrame(hk1)
In [17]:
hk2 = np.ones(topElev.shape)*0.1524 #0.03~1.53
hk3 = np.ones(topElev.shape)*10.16  #0.4~24.4

hk = [hk1, hk2, hk3]
hk = np.array(hk)
In [18]:
vka1 = np.ones(topElev.shape)*3.05e-7  # 3.05E-8~3.05E-5
vka2 = np.ones(topElev.shape)*3.05E-5  # 3.05E-5~3.05E-4
vka3 = np.ones(topElev.shape)*3.05E-5  # 3.05E-7~3.05E-2

vka = [vka1, vka2, vka3]  # Is equal to vert. K because of LAYVKA = 0
vka = np.array(vka)
In [19]:
ss1 = np.ones(topElev.shape)*0.15
ss2 = np.ones(topElev.shape)*0.0001
ss = [ss1, ss2, ss2]
ss = np.array(ss)
In [20]:
sy = 0.25 # 0.2~0.3

upw = flopy.modflow.ModflowUpw(
    mf,
    laytyp=laytyp,
    layavg=layavg,
    chani=chani,
    layvka=layvka,
    laywet=laywet,
    ipakcb=53,
    hdry=hdry,
    iphdry=iphdry,
    hk=hk,
    vka=vka,
    ss=ss,
    sy=sy,
)

# Basic Package setup: 
# bondary conditions: Constant-head boundaries on the edges of model
ibnd1_pth = os.path.join(
    "..",
    "input",
    "Bas",
    "layer1bnd.csv",
)

ibnd1 = np.loadtxt(ibnd1_pth)
ibnd1 = np.reshape(ibnd1, (345, 529))

ibnd2_pth = os.path.join(
    "..",
    "input",
    "Bas",
    "layer2bnd.csv",

Instantiate dispersion (DSP) package for MT3D-USGS¶

In [40]:
# Instantiate dispersion (DSP) package for MT3D-USGS: Dispersion can 
# follow the same mathematics used for diffusion, but it is due not 
# to molecular motion but to flow.
al = 0.83  # AL is the longitudinal dispersivity, L, for every cell of the model grid (unit, L). 
           # New Hampshire Department of Environmental Services File No. 5612.00 9/29/2023 
trpt = 0.1  # ratio of the horizontal transverse dispersivity to 'AL'
trpv = 0.01  # ratio of the vertical transverse dispersitvity to 'AL'

# mcomp = 4 must set in Btn package, dmcoef=comp1, dmcoef2=comp2...
# DMCOEF is the effective molecular diffusion coefficient (unit, L2T-1). 
dmcoef = 5.18e-5*prsity
dmcoef2 = 6.57e-5*prsity
dmcoef3 = 9.94e-5*prsity
dmcoef4 = 4.32e-5*prsity

dsp = flopy.mt3d.Mt3dDsp(
    mt, 
    al=al, 
    trpt=trpt, 
    trpv=trpv, 
    dmcoef=dmcoef, 
    dmcoef2=dmcoef2, 
    dmcoef3=dmcoef3, 
    dmcoef4=dmcoef4, 
    multiDiff=True,
)
